article.description:
Kerry Kittles scored 20 points, while Jason
Kidd added 17 points and 10 assists as the New Jersey Nets snapped
the New Orleans Hornets eight-game winning streak with a 102-92
victory on Sunday night.
article.headline: Nets snap Hornets' eight-game winning streak
article.linkText: Scalabrine the key factor as Nets stop Hornets
article.story:
NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Brian Scalabrine said he spent his time on the bench studying the moves of great players around the league, waiting for a chance to see if he could put some of them use.
Brian Scalabrine
Power Forward
New Jersey Nets
Profile
2002-2003 SEASON STATISTICS
GM PPG RPG APG FG% FT%
44 3.0 2.1 0.8 .420 .840
With the New Jersey Nets coming into New Orleans on a four-game losing skid and badly in need of a spark, the lumbering, 6-foot-9 Scalabrine tied a season high with 16 points as the Nets ended the Hornets' eight-game winning streak with a 102-92 victory Sunday night. ''I thought he was obviously one of the main keys to us winning this game. He was huge,'' Nets coach Byron Scott said. Scalabrine, who averages three points a game and goes by the nickname ''Veal,'' scored on a variety of drives, mid-range jumpers and the only 3-pointer he took. At one point in the fourth quarter, he even forced the Hornets to call a timeout by denying Kenny Anderson the ball on an inbounds play. ''You actually learn a lot on the bench about being aggressive,'' Scalabrine said. ''We've played a lot of great teams recently and I'm always trying to pick things up.'' The Hornets were clearly surprised by Scalabrine's production. ''He just came out of nowhere, hitting running hooks and jump shots and rebounding,'' Hornets forward P.J. Brown said. ''He was a big factor.'' Kerry Kittles, who was sharp from outside, scored 20 points for the Nets, while Jason Kidd added 17 points and 10 assists despite soreness in his left Achilles' tendon, which he said nearly kept him out of the game. ''I told (Scott) I'd give it a shot,'' Kidd said. ''I was just going to try anything to help the team and get us going in the right direction. We came with energy in the first quarter and I think that set the tone for the rest of the game.'' The Nets, coming off one of their worst performances of the season in an 83-71 defeat at Houston on Saturday night, played desperate, hustling, fastbreak basketball. ''Tonight I told them our backs are against the wall and there's two things you can do. You can either take a you-know-what whipping or you can give one, and our guys came out fighting tonight,'' Scott said. Kenyon Martin finished several breaks with dunks in a 19-point performance for the Nets. Richard Jefferson added 17 on 7-for-10 shooting while holding Hornets leading scorer Jamal Mashburn to a relatively low 18 points. Martin, however, was not willing to assert that the Nets, who had lost seven of eight games coming in, had snapped out of their recent funk. ''I don't know. It's just one game,'' Martin said. ''We did play well. We came out and played like we normally play.'' David Wesley led New Orleans with 24 points. Jamaal Magloire had 13 points and nine rebounds for the Hornets, while Brown scored 12 and Anderson 10 off the bench. New Jersey led most of the game and pushed its lead as high as 14 early in the third quarter with a 7-0 run. During the spurt Martin dunked on a fastbreak, Kidd hit a fallaway for his first basket of the game and Kittles hit a 3-pointer. New Orleans chipped away and cut the lead to six on a driving layup by Anderson, but then Kidd found Martin for an alley-oop dunk as New Jersey re-established control. ''I just thought we were slow,'' Hornets coach Paul Silas said. ''If we would have played our normal game I think we would have beaten that club. It's not a big concern. Basically, we just didn't have it tonight.'' New Jersey used a 10-0 run, powered by Martin, to open up an early 26-19 lead. Martin hit an inside shot off the glass, converted a fastbreak feed from Kidd and then dunked when Lucious Harris found him on a baseline cut. New Orleans, expected to get Baron Davis back Tuesday from a knee injury that knocked him out of action in late January, went 13-7 without their star guard. The defeat Sunday prevented New Orleans from pulling into a tie with Philadelphia for fourth in the Eastern Conference. Game notes
The Nets' Aaron Williams left the game in the second half with a strained right hamstring. ... Wesley has scored in double figures in 30 consecutive games. ... Kittles is from New Orleans and filled about 40 ticket requests for his first game as a professional in his hometown.
